[49m[38;5;10m+      37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Operational Specifications
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Latency Budget
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The real-time eligibility lookup API serves the registration workflow. The latency budget:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Path | P50 Target | P95 Target | P99 Target |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------|-----------|-----------|-----------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cache hit (Redis) | < 10ms | < 25ms | < 50ms |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cache miss, DynamoDB hit | < 50ms | < 100ms | < 200ms |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cache miss, DynamoDB miss, trigger async | < 200ms | < 500ms | < 2s |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The "verification in progress" response is the fail-open pattern: the registration workflow continues with a degraded-but-useful answer while the actual 270/271 round-trip happens asynchronously. The CAQH CORE Phase II SLA allows up to 20 seconds for the underlying 271; the cache-and-async pattern decouples registration latency from that round-trip. CloudWatch alarms fire when the async-resolution queue depth exceeds 500 records or persists more than 10 minutes (in steady state, the backlog should drain quickly).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Identity-Boundary Policy
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Each pipeline stage has a scoped trust boundary:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Inquiry-submission Lambda.** Accepts a `caller_context.invocation_source` enum: `registration_event`, `scheduled_pre_warm`, `batch_reconciliation`, `charity_care_screening`, `refresh_on_invalidation`. Each source maps to a caller IAM role; the Lambda validates the role before processing. Per-source rate limits prevent a runaway batch job from consuming registration-flow capacity (registration: 100 TPS ceiling; batch reconciliation: 50 TPS ceiling; others: 20 TPS ceiling).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Response-evaluation Lambda.** Verifies the cryptographic signature (where the partner signs the 271) or the TLS session identity on the clearinghouse response. Rejects replays by checking `(control_number, transaction_set_id)` against a DynamoDB dedup table with a 7-day TTL. A replayed or unsigned 271 routes to the DLQ with a logged `response_integrity_violation` metric.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Persist-eligibility-match function.** Validates that the `matched_member_id` in the response corresponds to the payer the inquiry targeted; a mismatch (wrong payer returned, or response routed to wrong inquiry) is rejected with a logged metric and DLQ routing. The conditional write uses `inquiry_hash` to enforce idempotency.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Eligibility-lookup read endpoint.** Applies privacy-suppression-on-read for patients with active privacy flags (42 CFR Part 2 patients, domestic-violence-sensitive records, VIP patients per institutional policy). Audit-logs every read with the caller identity, the patient_id, and the timestamp. The raw 271 audit payload is accessible only through a separate access-controlled path restricted to payer-relations and audit teams; clinical and revenue-cycle staff see the parsed coverage view only.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Cohort-Stratified Accuracy Monitoring
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Metrics are sourced from the institutional cohort registry (no ad-hoc demographic enumeration in code). Three metrics, each computed weekly or monthly:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Cadence | Disparity Threshold | Alarm Severity |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|---------|---------------------|----------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Per-cohort eligibility-match success rate (percent of inquiries returning AUTO_ACCEPT) | Weekly | > 0.05 absolute difference between best-rate and worst-rate cohort | MEDIUM |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Per-cohort review-queue rate (percent routed to human review) | Weekly | > 0.05 | MEDIUM |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Per-cohort claim-denial-for-eligibility rate (downstream metric tying matcher quality to revenue impact) | Monthly | > 0.03 | HIGH |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Alarms route to revenue-cycle and data-quality teams with a 5-business-day SLA. Remediation options: per-cohort threshold tuning, payer-specific normalization rules for affected naming patterns, registration-staff training on data capture for affected cohorts. All remediations documented in a cohort-disparity ledger and reviewed quarterly by the equity-monitoring committee.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Cross-Recipe Event Contract
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Eligibility events conform to the chapter-wide schema:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "source": "eligibility-matching",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "detail_type": "eligibility_resolved | eligibility_invalidated | eligibility_discrepancy_detected",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "detail": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "patient_id": "...",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "event_id": "...",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "previous_state": "...",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "new_state": "...",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "detected_at": "..."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Downstream consumers subscribe to specific `detail_type` values:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 5.1 (patient matcher):** subscribes to `eligibility_resolved` when the match surfaces a previously unknown duplicate-patient signal (same member ID matched to two patient_ids).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 5.5 (cross-facility HIE):** subscribes to `eligibility_resolved` when eligibility data from one facility's payer affects record reconciliation at another.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 5.6 (claims-to-clinical linkage):** subscribes to `eligibility_resolved` and `eligibility_invalidated` because eligibility state at time of service constrains claim-to-encounter joining.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Revenue-cycle pipeline:** subscribes to `eligibility_resolved` and `eligibility_invalidated` for claim-coverage refresh.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Charity-care workflow:** subscribes to `eligibility_resolved` for coverage-absent confirmation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Care-management pipeline:** subscribes to `eligibility_resolved` for high-deductible flagging.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Patient-portal pipeline:** subscribes to `eligibility_resolved` for benefits-view refresh.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Each consumer acknowledges processing via a CloudWatch metric (`{consumer}.events_processed`). Unacknowledged events older than 15 minutes trigger an alarm for the consuming team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Idempotency Keys and DLQ Topology
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Each pipeline stage has a recipe-specific idempotency key and a dedicated DLQ:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Stage | Idempotency Key | DLQ |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------|----------------|-----|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | normalize-inquiry | `inquiry_hash` | `normalize-inquiry-dlq` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | submit-inquiry | `inquiry_hash` + `clearinghouse_idempotency_key` | `submit-inquiry-dlq` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | evaluate-response | `(inquiry_id, response_payload_hash)` | `evaluate-response-dlq` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | persist-and-propagate | `(patient_id, payer_id, service_date, resolved_at_minute_bucket)` | `persist-match-dlq` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | invalidate-on-coverage-change | `(change_event_source, change_event_id)` | `invalidate-cache-dlq` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Step Functions Catch states route terminal failures to the stage-specific DLQ. CloudWatch alarms on DLQ depth surface stuck workflows within 15 minutes of accumulation. The operations team reviews DLQ contents daily; unresolvable items escalate to engineering within 24 hours.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### API Gateway and WAF Posture
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The eligibility-lookup API is a Private API with a VPC endpoint resource policy. Institutional consumers (registration system, PMS, revenue-cycle applications) reach the API through the VPC endpoint; no public internet path exists.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m AWS WAF is attached with rule groups for: SQL injection prevention, command injection prevention, request rate limiting per source-IP (1000 req/min) and per Cognito principal (500 req/min), and request-size limiting (16 KB max body). Blocked requests emit a CloudWatch metric for security-team review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### ElastiCache Cluster Sizing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m At a medium-volume institution doing 150K verifications per month, the rolling 12 months of past entries plus the 30-day forward window totals approximately 3-4 GB at 1-2 KB per match-outcome JSON. Starting point: `cache.r6g.large` (approximately 13 GB memory) with two read replicas and a `volatile-lfu` eviction policy. The past-service-date TTL of 1 year is conservative; institutions optimizing for cache cost may shorten to 30-90 days with on-demand re-fetch from DynamoDB on the rare past-date read.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CloudWatch alarms: memory utilization > 80% signals undersizing; per-day eviction count above 1000 signals either undersizing or a cache-invalidation storm. Cost: approximately $400-800/month for `cache.r6g.large` with replicas at the stated volumes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Lake Formation Access Controls
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Three audiences need different views of the eligibility data:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Audience | Data Scope | Access Method |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |----------|-----------|---------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Payer-relations and audit teams | Raw 271 payloads (full coverage and financial-responsibility detail) | Lake Formation column-level grant on raw zone; restricted IAM role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Clinical and revenue-cycle staff | Parsed coverage state (plan active/inactive, copay, deductible status) | Lake Formation column-level grant on curated zone; standard operational IAM role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Leadership and equity-monitoring committees | Cohort-aggregated metrics (no individual patient detail) | Lake Formation row-level filter on derived zone; read-only dashboard IAM role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Direct Athena query path uses the same Lake Formation grants. Access logged via CloudTrail data events on the Glue Catalog and underlying S3 buckets.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Cohort-Bucketed Metric Dimensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m When emitting cohort dimensions on CloudWatch metrics, use bucketed non-reversible cohort labels (`cohort_bucket` = A, B, C, D, E, unknown) rather than raw demographic attributes. The cohort-label-to-attribute mapping lives in a separate access-controlled DynamoDB table loaded only at dashboard-render time by the equity-monitoring committee's IAM role. This prevents demographic re-identification from CloudWatch metric dimensions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Clearinghouse Data-Handling Commitments
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The clearinghouse BAA and trading-partner agreement must specify:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 1. The partner will not retain submitted patient data beyond a documented operational window (typical clearinghouse retention is 7 years for HIPAA audit purposes; operational caches are typically days-to-weeks and must be specified separately).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 2. The partner will disclose all sub-processors that may handle PHI in the eligibility-verification flow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 3. The partner will notify the institution within 72 hours of any data incident affecting the eligibility transaction data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 4. The institution retains the right to audit the partner's controls annually.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The 270 inquiry contains full patient demographics plus the patient_id. The patient_id is a partner-shared identifier under BAA (not a public identifier); document this in the inquiry-submission code as a de-identification-posture annotation so future engineers understand why the patient_id travels to the partner.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Clearinghouse Egress Configuration
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Clearinghouse egress and direct-payer egress use distinct outbound proxy rules with non-overlapping allow-lists scoped to compute roles. Each Lambda role allows only the specific partner endpoints it must call. Per-role rate limits are set below the partner's published rate limits (prevent a single consumer from exhausting the partner's allocation). Egress connections are CloudWatch-logged for chargeback and forensic auditing. At eligibility-inquiry volumes (millions per month for medium institutions), evaluate the partner's PrivateLink endpoints where available.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Review-Queue Audit Posture
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Every review decision records:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The reviewer's identity (authenticated via Cognito or institutional SSO)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The decision: accept, reject, escalate, or request-info
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The reviewer's stated reason (free text)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - The `THRESHOLDS_VERSION` active at the time of the match
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Any reviewer-supplied additional demographic context (for example, "patient confirmed maiden name was Garcia, married name is Smith")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The audit trail supports forensic reconstruction when a wrong match is later traced back to a reviewer decision. It also supports periodic gold-set re-evaluation that catches systematic reviewer biases (for example, a reviewer who auto-accepts all search matches above 0.70 without reading the address comparator). Review decisions feed the active-learning loop for periodic threshold re-calibration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Records Retention Policy
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Retention floor: the longer of 7 years (HIPAA records-retention minimum), 10 years (Medicare claims retention where applicable), the institution's documented eligibility-data retention policy, the value-based-care contract retention requirement (where applicable), and any state-specific Medicaid retention requirement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Implementation: audit logs in a dedicated S3 bucket with Object Lock in Compliance mode for immutability. Lifecycle policy transitions objects to S3 Glacier Deep Archive after 90 days. CloudTrail data events forwarded to a dedicated audit AWS account in the institution's organization, isolating the audit substrate from the production data plane. The retention floor is enforced at the bucket-policy and Object-Lock-configuration level, not at application logic.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Threshold Calibration Governance
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thresholds (`AUTO_ACCEPT_THRESHOLD`, `AUTO_REJECT_THRESHOLD`, per-feature weights in the composite score) live in a versioned configuration table in DynamoDB. Re-calibration runs annually or on detection of cohort-stratified disparity above 0.05, whichever comes first. The re-calibration process:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 1. Produces a candidate threshold set from the current gold-set evaluation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 2. Institutional review (revenue-cycle leadership, compliance, equity-monitoring committee) reviews the confusion matrix and the cohort-disparity impact.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 3. Approved candidates promote to production with a new `THRESHOLDS_VERSION`.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 4. Each match outcome records the configuration version and threshold values active at inference time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Change without governance is the failure mode that produces silent regressions in both accuracy and equity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Scoped Resource ARN Examples
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Highest-stakes actions use scoped Resource ARNs:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m dynamodb:UpdateItem  on arn:aws:dynamodb:<region>:<account>:table/eligibility-match
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m s3:PutObject         on arn:aws:s3:::<env>-eligibility-raw/audit/*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m events:PutEvents     on arn:aws:events:<region>:<account>:event-bus/eligibility-events
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m secretsmanager:GetSecretValue on arn:aws:secretsmanager:<region>:<account>:secret:clearinghouse/*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Never use `*` resource ARNs in production. Each Lambda role receives only the specific table, bucket prefix, event bus, and secret path it requires.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Backfill Discipline
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The initial backfill at launch follows the chapter pattern from recipes 5.1, 5.2, and 5.3:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 1. Negotiate bulk pricing with the clearinghouse before backfill (batch transaction pricing is 5-10x cheaper than real-time).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 2. Run as a Glue job with controlled concurrency below the clearinghouse's rate limit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 3. Suppress `eligibility_resolved` event emission during backfill; downstream consumers refresh from a single `eligibility_backfill_complete` marker.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 4. Emit one `eligibility_backfill_complete` event when done, with the cohort-stratified accuracy report attached.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 5. Plan the backfill timeline in coordination with downstream consumers (PMS, revenue cycle, charity care) so the change in eligibility-data quality lands on a known date.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
